s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the majority of which are small businesses or sole traders. PPL generated revenue of over £170m in 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PPL’s broadcast and online </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">licensing covers the use of recorded music on the BBC’s television, radio and iPlayer services and by hundreds of commercial broadcasters. These include ITV, Channel 4, Five and BSkyB, together with services such as Virgin Media and BT Vision. These licenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es often cover a range of new media uses of recorded music in addition to “traditional” broadcasts. PPL also licenses commercial radio networks such as Capital, Heart and Absolute Radio, online services such as Last.fm, and community, hospital, student and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> prison radio stations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As regards the BBC, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he licence granted by PPL provides the BBC with the right to include recorded music controlled by PPL’s members within the wide range of services operated by the BBC, including its radio and television broadcasts and digital services such as the BBC iPlaye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r. PPL also licenses BBC Worldwide for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">various uses of r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecorded music</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PPL welcomes the opportunity to make a submission to the Inquiry.  PPL notes the remit of the Inquiry and the questions set out in the Inquiry’s call for evidence. Many of the topics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">covered by the call for evidence are matters in respect of which, given its role as a music licensing company, PPL is not best placed to comment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, PPL can offer evidence in the form of its experiences of licensing the BBC (and BBC Worldwide) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any years, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icularly with regard to those aspects of the call for evidence which focus on the public purposes set out in the current Charter. PPL hopes that the information it is able to provide will be of some assistance to the Culture, Media and Sport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Committee as it considers further the matters covered by the Inquiry. </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The BBC’s principal radio services broadcast a substantially wider range of sound recordings than equivalent commercial radio services. Not only does this contribute to its public purpose of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“stimulating creativity and cultural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">excellence”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, it also provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> wider o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pportunity for new sound recordings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and new recording artists to be heard by the public, which is important for the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> health and success of the UK m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">usic industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Through the international transmissions of its music radio services and the d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">istribution (by BBC Worldwide) of televisi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">on programmes which include UK m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">usic, the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">helps to meet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> its public purpose of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“bringing the UK to the world”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s the global success of the UK m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">usic industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In launching new digital services such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (as an example of fulfilling its public purpose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">helping to deliver to the public the benefit of emerging communications technologies and services”)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the BBC has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">favoured a collective licensing approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and this has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">paved the way for PPL’s c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ollective licensing of similar services by commercial providers, thereby wide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ning the scope of legitimate on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">line services in the UK. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">As a general observ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ation, PPL notes that the BBC (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">as a music</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> user on a considerable scale) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">demonstrates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> due respect for th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e need to obtain legal clearance for the rights to use PPL’s members’ recordings.  It also observe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> due process, with the licensing terms being agreed by way of robust arm’s-lengt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">h negotiations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and by reference to appropriate compar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ators in the commercial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, whilst always recognising that the BBC must make appropriate payment for such rights.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">For ease of reference, PPL’s comments below are pres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ented under the headings of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">public purposes from the current Charter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.68pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CREATIVITY AND CULTURAL EXCELLENCE</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PPL’s experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">generally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">makes use of a wider range of different sound recordings than equivalent commercial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">broadcasting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">services. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is based on the reporting information provided by PPL’s broadcasting licensees.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to appropriately </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">distribute royalties to its members, PPL requires its licensees </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report details of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recordings that have been used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under their licences, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the extent of such usage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. PPL then pays its members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">based on this usage information (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">applying the same methodo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">logy whether the recording is owned by major record companies, independent labels or self-releasing artists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By way of example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">27,868</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">different unique</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recordings were played on BBC R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adio 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is significantly higher than the equivalent number on any commercial radio station</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the same period,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can be compared to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1,375 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unique recordings played on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Heart network of stations and 4,073 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unique recordings played on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Magic network of stations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is reasonable to assume that s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ourcing and selecting this larger range of recordings is likely to require investment of time and effort that is unlikely to be recreated by a service operating in the commercial sector. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> BBC is also a member of PPL in its rol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e as the owner of a substantial amount of commercial music. New music commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed by the BBC adds to the world-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leading UK repertoire of music, particularly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the classical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">genre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">BRINGING THE UK TO THE WORLD AND TH</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">E WORLD TO THE UK</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK is a net exporter of recorded music</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> adding to the UK’s balance of trade and helping to promote the UK and British culture in a wider sense. By way of example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recordings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> made up 12% of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> US recorded music </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">market and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">four out of five of the top selling albums in the US were from UK artists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </spa